From 156ba70fe108261a56badf2d448904110e056456 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Masahito S <firelzrd@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 28 Mar 2026 09:15:43 +0900
Subject: [PATCH] sched/fair: add starvation-aware migration candidate
 selection fix-1
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Introduce CONFIG_SCHED_STARV_MIGRATE, a load-balancing enhancement that
replaces the plain cfs_tasks list walk with a per-rq rbtree
(starv_timeline) ordered by a normalized migration suitability score.

Score formula: gap * inv_weight * 960 >> 32
  - gap = max(0, runnable_avg - util_avg)  (branchless)
  - inv_weight from se->load (heavier tasks get smaller scores)
  - 960 normalizes to full u16 range (65535 at nice 19 full contention)

The rbtree is ordered ascending, so the leftmost node (O(1) access) is
the heaviest, least-starved task — the ideal migration candidate that
resolves imbalance efficiently and is unlikely to need re-migration.

Implementation details:
  - starv_node added to sched_entity; starv_timeline (rb_root_cached)
    added to struct rq
  - Scores updated inline during PELT updates in pelt.c; rbtree
    requeued on score change in update_load_avg()
  - detach_tasks() refactored: common detach_candidate() helper shared
    by both starv (rbtree) and list (original) paths
  - Runtime-togglable via /proc/sys/kernel/sched_starv_migrate (default 1)
  - Disabled for SMT siblings (SD_SHARE_CPUCAPACITY)
---
 include/linux/sched.h |   6 +
 init/Kconfig          |  16 +++
 kernel/sched/core.c   |   3 +
